Alert Status Monitoring--Peak & Valley

Summary
Peak/Valley are designed for the analysts to monitor the status of the different camera alerts in priority when the count of alerts is passing the threshold we set.
Once a peak/valley notification is sent to the analyst, that means there is a merge increase or suddenly decrease in the count of a specific alert. There is a higher possibility that this camera is in an abnormal status and needs to be monitored in priority.
In this way, the analysts could go to the dashboard of the records of this camera from spider to view the historical records for this specific camera, which could make the monitor work to be more efficient.
The monitoring is almost in-time. We get the alerts counting data from the Teradata database. By selecting the useful columns and applying the necessary counting mode, we are regenerating the tables.
The function has enough flexibility to allow the user to change the size of parameters based on different matrices.
The basic matrix we applied in the functions are:
•	Lag, we will need this to decide the range of data we select when we apply the statistical models. Since we have long historical data, the peak/valley will be different based on which data frame we use.
•	Threshold: Result will be different if we set different values to the threshold, the alerts will be sent in a higher frequency if a lower threshold has been set. In the other way, a lower frequency of alerts email being received if a lower threshold value has been set.
•	Influence: The basic logic to detect the peak/valley is the same, of which the fundamental is to detect the abnormal cases among the historical records. So we could set the influence parameters in an opposite way to distinguish in which circumstance we are applying this function.
•	Alert type (Camera name) : Different alert_name as one of the variables.
Components:
•	Detect peak/valley
•	Plotting in charts
•	Send email, email content design


